Virgil's “ Gathering of the Clans ''

I do not believe that Virgil would have written these six lines of description, the portrait of a savage chieftain in war-paint, to mark the hero of a hill on the site of Rome, and within a stone’s throw of the city of the civilized Evander, to be described in the next book. I will therefore write them here as fol- lowing on the description of Ufens, and leave it to the reader to decide whether or no they may be thought to belong there:

“ et te montosae misere in praelia Nursae, Ufens, insignem fama et felicibus armis, horrida praecipue cui gens adsuetaque multo venatu nemorum, duris Aequicola glebis. Armati terram exercent semperque recentis convectare iuvat praedas et vivere rapto. pila manu saevosque gerunt in bella dolones, et tereti pugnant mucrone veruque Sabello.
